  "Prerequisites": "Learners should have a basic familiarity with using digital tools or online platforms, and an interest in how artificial intelligence is beginning to shape teaching and learning environments.",
  "Learning objectives": "By the end of this course, you will be able to identify the key risks associated with student dependency on AI tools and explain how over-reliance on these technologies can hinder the development of essential academic and critical thinking skills. You will also apply practical strategies to recognise early signs of AI dependency in learning environments and support students in building genuine, lasting competencies alongside responsible AI use.",
  "lessons": [
    {
      "lesson title": "AI in Education: When Learning Becomes Dependency",
      "order": 1,
      "Description": "This lesson explores the growing concern that students are turning to AI tools to complete their work rather than developing the foundational skills they need for long-term success. We will look at how over-reliance on AI can quietly erode critical thinking, writing ability, and problem-solving confidence, often without students even realising it is happening. Through practical examples and honest discussion, you will begin to recognise the difference between using AI as a helpful support and using it as a substitute for genuine learning. By the end of this lesson, you will have a clearer understanding of the risks involved and feel better equipped to make thoughtful, informed choices about how and when to use AI in your studies.",
